<br>
So please if you have time take a gander at this and i hope you are entertained.<br>
<br>
The Singing Blade<br>
<br>
The fireball exploded in the middle of the flanking squad and scattered them like a candlelight scatters cubbard bugs in the night. Bodies lay everywhere burning and broken and in the middle of it all Lt. Nindar craddled his sargents charde corpse close to him. The horde of orcs closed in all about him to finish off what was left of the rag tag bunch.<br>
<br>
A tear streamed down the young Lts. cheek for his first commission would end before it even began, uneventful and in shame. He drew his blade and stood ready to make one last valiant effort to save what little face he had left.<br>
<br>
The smell of burning flesh and the heated breathe of the whooping orc ban sent chills down the Lts. spine. A quick prayer to his god and he steadied himself for the pending charge.<br>
<br>
&quot;Squire bring my armor&quot; the first part of the verse of a haunting tune caught his ear.<br>
<br>
&quot;My sword and my destrire&quot; the second part cut through the grunts and snarls like a hot knife through butter.<br>
<br>
&quot;I've raised and army to break Kuluns power. Out from the southlands, we march to the battle, the banner of glory a flutt'rn around. So let loose your clothyard my stout forest bowman, the hiss of your bow strings as soft as a sigh. They'll pay what they owe thee, or fight on the morrow. The blood of the orcanny will soil the ground.&quot; The dirge seemed to come from everywhere and no where and froze the orc in place.<br>
<br>
The Lt. caught a glimpse of a white cloak fluttering about in the black sooty smoke rising in the air. A you man strolled into view with a catlike grace, moving with the rhythm of the tune he sang, as if he where at a ball in the Kings castle itself. Behind him marched three score men all with a determined scowl upon their faces to match the look of the singer. The orc turned to face their new threat and a pause hung in the air ten heartbeats long to signify a beat change.<br>
<br>
The surroundings exploded into action as if on cue. Blades flashed , blood flew, grunts and groans escaped the lips of the injured. The Lt. stood stupified as his eyes never left his white cloaked saviors form. The young mans feet danced inches off the ground as he whirled, ducked and dodged his way through the frey. An orc advanced to the young mans left and he turned his head and a banshee wail escaped his lips and the orc turned tail and ran out of sheer terror.<br>
<br>
The white cloaked man floated to a halt right in front of the Lt. shacking him back to reality. Confused, Lt. Nindar could have sworn he had been at least 100ft. or more away from him seconds ago.<br>
<br>
&quot;Are ye going to be putting that blade to use or are ye in need of a few more lessons?&quot; the white cloak man smiled and winked.<br>
<br>
&quot;Umm I.....umm I can fight sir.&quot; stammered Nindar<br>
<br>
&quot;Then be about it. I really would like to be back enjoying noondays feast.&quot; beaming a smile he twirled about bringing sword and hammer up in a cross block on the haft of a descending orc axe. He crouched to absorb the orcs power and leapt in the air spinning about to face the Lt. again. The orc fell to his right throat slit. &quot;Follow me.&quot; He shouted over his shoulder as he danced into the middle of the skirmish, white cloak flowing behind him like a cloud and a fresh new tune upon his lips cutting through the noise.<br>
<br>
The Lt. could not help but follow this charismatic man and found himself moving to the beat of the song, that filled him with power and courage. &quot;There might be a chance to pull this off.&quot; he thought to himself. &quot;I to would rather be enjoying noondays feast.&quot; Nindar chuckled aloud. &quot;Oh my gods i am in a fight for my life and i stand here cracking jokes. Who is this man and how does he inspire with a song and a smile?&quot; Nindar rushed forward so's he would not lose sight of this young man.<br>
